76561198116953146,Recommended,293340,17125304,"Posted: 19 July, 2015",all,Turtleswatter,"Firstly, this is an unusual game and, looking at the forums the developers are very happy to tweak and improve.  Their obvious intent is to make it as good as it can be.  For this reason I’m recommending it.  There isn’t a lot of experimentation with genre these days and they deserve the credit for having a go and persevering.  I hope that one day my game will be better as they patch it.  And the overall feel is such that even though the gameplay is driving me to distraction I’m still trying!However, there are some cons that are close to game breakers for me.  It feels as if it should be a happy, casual game with a few teeth to make it a bit more exciting – storms, pirates etc.  It also feels as if the random tasks you have to do while trying to get your passengers from A to B within a time frame should be fun and lift the pace a bit.Unfortunately, as it stands at the moment playing this game is a chore purely because, despite experimenting with lots of different combinations of settings, the controls are, quite frankly, awful.With my basic gaming computer set up, the boat controls are fine and as they should be, as long as you realise that these are boats and not racing cars.  However the big problem is the camera and mouse controls which are fantastically erratic.The mouse control is laggy, which means that you have to spend way too much time trying to hit a button resulting in loss of control of your boat. I have since found that if you go into your computer control panel and turn the mouse sensitivity down to the slowest you can, the situation - although not perfect - improves dramatically. The camera angles are poor.  On the face of it, as you are given 4 different camera positions, you should be able to easily see whatever you need to.  Unfortunately 2 of them have very limited use – why would I want to see inside the boat unless I’m happy to crash?  The third, I haven’t been able to find a use for and the default one, the one that you are almost constantly using, is a nightmare.In order to look around, you have to hold the left mouse button down and move the mouse in the direction you want to see (up, down and around).  This control varies wildly from fair, where you can see everything with very little effort; to ultra sensitive where the slightest touch leaves you looking at a scene and you have no idea where you are (please remember the boat is still moving at this point - well until the harbour wall stops it).  Alternatively you can end up looking at the bottom of the sea.  The problem here is that it seems to become ultra sensitive when you need it to behave most – such as when you’re trying to dock. Compare this with the lagginess of the mouse when you need to use it to click on things and the whole thing just doesn’t make sense.The sensitivity is an issue when you are trying to take photographs. You find your bird.  You point your boat in the right direction and hold the right hand mouse button down.  Sadly you see a piece of blue sky with absolutely no idea where in the sky you are.  You wave your mouse about in the hope you might catch the bird.  No luck.  You go into the normal view and find the bird again – to be fair not very far from where it was initially.  Try again.  No luck.  Eventually you glimpse the tip of the wing and you realise how fast your mouse is scanning the sky – you’re hardly touching it but it’s going so fast that by the time you realise you’ve seen the tip of the wing, you’ve got no chance of backtracking and finding it again. Rinse and repeat until you luck out.  Absolutely no way can you do this when you’ve got a passenger on board.Having said all this everything else is lovely – which is why, along with the developers, I’m persevering with it.  It’s just that this could easily become my favourite casual game and it’s frustrating to have it spoilt by the controls."
76561198121073226,Recommended,293340,15422431,"Posted: 17 April, 2015",all,Marcus 7x9y,"It is not such a bad game. But it is more an arcade-action and a game of skills. Every 2 to 4 trips pirats are coming into your line trying to damage your boat, every 2 to 4 trips tornados are coming into your line. For a simulation game a bit to unrealististic and very nervy. Very nervy are the camera controls, both with mouse and gamepad. The bigger your ship, more problems with controlling in side missions. I am not so happy with it.There could be more informations about docking stations to the map before you agree into a customer's contract. F.e. distance from current location and a list of it. An option is missing to get more passengers in one journey.If you run into a sandbar, don't think about to call for help. There is no option given in this game. You can load your game save by hoping that the sandbar will release you, but it depends on how deep you ran into it.You can change your bought boats at each docking station if you like.But I can give this one my recommendation because of the atmosphere of this game and all the skills you have to use making this one very special. All in all a nice game with interesting challenges. :)"
